07469nam a22010335i 9780812290332DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979577568  a97808122903327 a10.9783/97808122903322doi  a(DE-B1597)451242  a(OCoLC)910456043  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0220002bisacsh04a303.6096223  aMI 100502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122923:1203900aConstitutions and Conflict Management in Africa :bPreventing Civil War Through Institutional Design /ced. by Alan J. Kuperman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b22 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational and Ethnic Conflict in the 21st Century00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1. Designing Constitutions to Reduce Domestic Conflict -- tACCOMMODATION IS RISKY -- t2. Burundi: Institutionalizing Ethnicity to Bridge the Ethnic Divide -- t3. Kenya: Gradual Pluralization Fails to Buffer Shocks -- t4. Nigeria: Devolution to Mitigate Conflict in the Niger Delta -- t5. Sudan: “Successful” Constitutional Reform Spurs Localized Violence -- tINTEGRATION CAN WORK -- t6. Ghana: The Complements of Successful Centralization: Checks, Balances, and Informal Accommodation -- t7. Senegal: The Limits of Hyper- Centralization -- t8. Zimbabwe: The Unintended Consequences of Authoritarian Institutions -- tAPPLYING THE LESSONS -- t9. Africa’s Domestic Institutions of Integration and Accommodation: A New Database -- t10. Rethinking Constitutional Reform for Democracy and Stability -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEach of Africa's countries has a different constitutional design, is characterized by a unique culture and history, and faces different stresses that threaten to undermine political stability. Presenting the first database of constitutional design in all African countries, along with seven original case studies, Constitutions and Conflict Management in Africa explores the types of domestic political institutions that can buffer societies from destabilizing changes that otherwise increase the risk of violence.With detailed comparative studies of Burundi, Ghana, Kenya, Nigeria, Senegal, Sudan, and Zimbabwe, contributing scholars identify key turning points at which a state's political institutions either mitigated or escalated the effects of economic, environmental, demographic, and political shocks. They find that stability can be promoted by various constitutional designs—not only by accommodative institutions that encourage decentralization and multiculturalism, but also by the integrative, centralized designs that characterize the constitutions of most African countries. The greatest danger may arise from partial or inequitable accommodation that can exacerbate societal tensions, culminating in violence up to and including civil war and genocide. Accordingly, Constitutions and Conflict Management in Africa cautions against the typical international prescription for radical reform to replace Africa's existing constitutions with accommodative designs, instead prescribing more gradual constitutional reform to strengthen liberal institutions, such as strong judiciaries and independent electoral commissions. This detailed and methodical volume provides vital lessons for fostering democracy and reducing civil conflict via constitutional reform in Africa and beyond.Contributors: Justin Orlando Frosini, Gilbert M. Khadiagala, Alan J. Kuperman, Karly Kupferberg, Eli Poupko, Eghosa E. Osaghae, Andrew Reynolds, Filip Reyntjens, Arame Tall, Hillary Thomas-Lake, Stefan Wolff, I. William Zartman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, vie